Can Stage be Component?
These are not exclusive to each other.
User ~= Some initialization + Netboot
Netboot = DHCP + download/extract file
Does this need more updating after with the final design doc?

Yes, it need...
I will set this CL `ready to review` after I updated.
I think you don't need to review it now since it might have huge change.
does this dump the json as a string?

You mean one-line string vs multiple-lines string?
I think it's multiple lines.
https://github.com/nlohmann/json#tofrom-streams-eg-files-string-streams
Need more detail on this service. Does it need to be internal?

Sorry I didn't get you point.
You are asking why do we need 2 similar functions `hostBootTimeSetDuration` and `dbusSetDuration`?
Or you are asking what's the purpose of `hostBootTimeSetDuration` and `hostBootTimeNotify`?

The answer for former one is that I need to mock `dbusSetDuration` in the unit test so that I can test `hostBootTimeSetDuration`.

The answer for later one is that this CL is supporting `btmanager`.
btmanager is a new added service for monitor the host boot process. The code is in the review process on openbmc/google-misc. https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/google-misc/+/54501/4
yeah, I just meant that we need more detail on what the service does. Can you link the change to the commit message?

I expected the `bus.call` returns a reply to me.
So I can read the information with this reply.
In this case can we still use `bus.call_noreply`?

oh wait. right, I missed the read. 

This is fine.
compare with the exact string instead?

Sure.
But I think both are find. In entity-manager we use `ends_with` to match dbus result.
https://github.com/openbmc/entity-manager/blob/master/src/fru_device.cpp#L1412-L1413
don't need else if when we return within statement.

just return dbusNotify(checkpointCode)

The try-catch doesn't really do anything in this case.

I think it's needed.
I tried this but it doesn't pass compile.
```
MOCK_METHOD(uint8_t, hostBootTimeSetDuration, ((const std::string&), uint64_t),
                (const, override));
```

try
```
MOCK_METHOD(uint8_t, hostBootTimeSetDuration,
                (const std::string&, uint64_t), (const, override));
```
Can we split the change to the dbus stuff from the host boot time?

Hi Willy,
Can we restart the review proccess of this CL?
I was being asked to enable this feature in an internal project.
So I need this CL to be merged.
I also asked reviewer the same stuff in https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/google-misc/+/54398
Is the decision to use `com.google.gbmc.btmanager` finalized?

The reason I wnat this CL to be merged is for internal use.
We can change it after this feature move to openbmc (instead of google-ipmi-sys)
then we can just carry this as a patch internally instead.
ok. After comments in this CL are resolved, I will create a internal patch.

wait...

Why is the data formatted like

length, name, durationMs?

Can we just change it to 

```
durationMs, length, name
```

so the dynamic size data is at the end?
Is this a convention? I don't see the differents.
the difference is that we always know where the data of each element starts. instead of having the start of durationMs being dynamic.

Ack and changed.

I put the name in the front becuase the <name, durationMs> is a key-value pair in my design.
I would like to confirm if it's worth to reverse the key-value order to achive what you mentioned?

One more scenario I want to confirm is that:
if the parameters are multiple but certain number(let's say **2** for example).
What's your preference? 
I think (1) matches your comment the most. But I think (3) is the most clear one.

`L=len, n=name, d=durationMs`

1.
```
<d1> <d2> <L1> <L2> <n1> <n2>
```

2.
```
<d1> <d2> <L1> <n1> <L2> <n2>
```

3.
```
<L1> <n1> <d1> <L2> <n2> <d2>
```
I will modify README and unittest after this is finalized.
I think you mean footer? But is this comment needed?

> I think you mean footer?
Ah yes, thanks for that.

> But is this comment needed?
Is telling user that this struct `HostBootTimeSetDurationRequestHeaderTailer` is not the full struct. It only contains `header` and `footer`.
